<rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" version="2.0"><channel><title>Mastodon Home Timeline</title><link>https://mastodon.social</link><description>RSS feed for the Mastodon Home timeline</description><docs>http://www.rssboard.org/rss-specification</docs><generator>python-feedgen</generator><lastBuildDate>Wed, 24 Jan 2024 22:15:55 +0000</lastBuildDate><item><title>:jan:‚Äç:abreath:‚Äç‚Äçüå¨:dandelion:</title><link>https://pagan.plus/@Crazypedia/111800729446732167</link><description>There is only one true God and they are Entropy and Decay :dancing_mushroom: :mario_mushroom: :moomin_mushroom: &lt;br/&gt;&lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://pagan.plus/tags/MushroomsOfMastodon" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;MushroomsOfMastodon&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&amp;gt; Think long and hard before buying oyster &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://pagan.plus/tags/mushroom" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;mushroom&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; blocks to grow in your house. They are a very aggressive &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://pagan.plus/tags/fungi" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;fungi&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and not at all picky on what types of wood they will consume.  If you have any moisture problems they will begin to eat your house. I see these posts constantly in my mushroom ID groups.  I started collecting pictures to show people so they could see the dangers themselves.  I have not noticed any warning labels of any kind on the packaging, so buyer beware.  If you have your heart set on growing mushrooms in your kitchen then I recommend that you pick any kind besides oysters.  Lion's mane, maitake, chestnuts or literally anything else beside oysters...unless you rent and don't like your landlord üòÜ&lt;br/&gt;Source: &lt;a href="https://www.facebook.com/100066986004312/posts/694630886113105/?mibextid=AQCFcj8imgClWYJ5" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;facebook.com/100066986004312/p&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;osts/694630886113105/?mibextid=AQCFcj8imgClWYJ5&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/101/885/596/original/25d7b55457e1242b.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/101/885/596/original/25d7b55457e1242b.jpg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/175/717/516/original/2bec39d5e1c6d621.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/175/717/516/original/2bec39d5e1c6d621.jpg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/225/644/844/original/e4c0983fef4f8f1f.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/225/644/844/original/e4c0983fef4f8f1f.jpg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/267/116/524/original/ed1603245dca6fbf.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://files.mastodon.social/cache/media_attachments/files/111/800/730/267/116/524/original/ed1603245dca6fbf.jpg" alt="Mastodon image" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111805533367281500</guid><pubDate>Tue, 23 Jan 2024 13:37:29 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Earl K. Miller</title><link>https://fediscience.org/@ekmiller/111805699276655620</link><description>Photographer trains rats to press a lever for food.  It also snaps a photo.  Photographer pretends rats are taking selfies.  Sigh.  NY Times reports this in the Science section.  Another sigh.Our Rodent Selfies, Ourselves &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/01/23/science/photography-rats-selfies.html?smid=nytcore-android-share" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;nytimes.com/2024/01/23/science&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;/photography-rats-selfies.html?smid=nytcore-android-share&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111805699313249538</guid><pubDate>Tue, 23 Jan 2024 14:19:41 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Virginia Dignum</title><link>https://mastodon.social/@vdignum/111806106876203098</link><description>A worrying scenario: billionaires recreating the &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mastodon.social/tags/scifi" rel="tag"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;scifi&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; scenarios at the cost of all of us...&lt;br/&gt;As I often say: the risk is not losing control over &lt;a class="mention hashtag" href="https://mastodon.social/tags/AI" rel="tag"&gt;#&lt;span&gt;AI&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, it is having no control over those people that have the power to control it. A very real risk.&lt;a href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/tech-billionaires-need-to-stop-trying-to-make-the-science-fiction-they-grew-up-on-real/" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" translate="no"&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;https://www.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="ellipsis"&gt;scientificamerican.com/article&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="invisible"&gt;/tech-billionaires-need-to-stop-trying-to-make-the-science-fiction-they-grew-up-on-real/&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">111806106876203098</guid><pubDate>Tue, 23 Jan 2024 16:03:20 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Earl K. Miller</title><link>https://fediscience.org/@ekmiller/111806135055803960</link><description>Ramping dynamics and theta oscillations reflect dissociable signatures during rule-guided human behavior&lt;br/&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s